TY  - JOUR
T1  - Effect of Risk Aversion on Single Sample Attribute Inspection Plans
AU  - Moskowitz, Herbert
AU  - Plante, Robert
Y1  - 1984/10/01
PY  - 1984
DA  - 1984/10/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.30.10.1226
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.30.10.1226
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 1226
EP  - 1237
VL  - 30
IS  - 10
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - The impact of a decision maker's risk aversion on the choice of an optimal sampling plan is empirically examined for various batch sizes and prior distributions of the process quality level. These plans are compared to those of the classical linear cost model. The comparisons show that substantial differences in the characteristics of an optimal sampling plan (i.e., probability of acceptance, optimal sample size and expected total cost) occur when risk aversion is considered. A discussion of the optimization characteristics involved in the selection of a sampling plan is also presented. An optimization algorithm which obtains an optimal sampling plan based on the criterion of maximizing expected utility is proposed and evaluated.
AB  - The impact of a decision maker's risk aversion on the choice of an optimal sampling plan is empirically examined for various batch sizes and prior distributions of the process quality level. These plans are compared to those of the classical linear cost model. The comparisons show that substantial differences in the characteristics of an optimal sampling plan (i.e., probability of acceptance, optimal sample size and expected total cost) occur when risk aversion is considered. A discussion of the optimization characteristics involved in the selection of a sampling plan is also presented. An optimization algorithm which obtains an optimal sampling plan based on the criterion of maximizing expected utility is proposed and evaluated.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.30.10.1226
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.30.10.1226
Y2  - 2024/03/28
